Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.90,0:00:05.23,Default,,0,0,0,,The next part is a video \Nentitled The Inside Story, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.23,0:00:08.15,Default,,0,0,0,,hosted by Brother Ken Stovall, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.15,0:00:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,who also serves \Nas a Theocratic Schools instructor.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.02,0:00:45.82,Default,,0,0,0,,I am so excited to be with you here again \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.82,0:00:48.15,Default,,0,0,0,,on this segment of The Inside Story! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.15,0:00:52.53,Default,,0,0,0,,This time we’re \Nwith class number 143 of the Gilead School, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.53,0:00:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,and you are going to meet \Nsome adorable brothers and sisters. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.37,0:00:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,And let me tell you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.49,0:01:01.04,Default,,0,0,0,,they have some moving experiences \Nto relate to you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.04,0:01:05.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And we’re going to solve \Ntwo fascinating mysteries. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.17,0:01:06.17,Default,,0,0,0,,And we have music. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.17,0:01:08.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Students in this class are going \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.63,0:01:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,to thrill you with their musical talent. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.72,0:01:14.26,Default,,0,0,0,,There is a captivating song \Nthat they’re going to sing for you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.26,0:01:17.89,Default,,0,0,0,,So come with me as we, together, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.89,0:01:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,get “the inside story.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:23.31,0:01:25.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s introduce our first guest. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.11,0:01:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And that would be Saša Komaromi \Nfrom the Serbia branch.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.53,0:01:42.16,Default,,0,0,0,,So, Brother Komaromi, \Nyou serve at the Serbia branch. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.16,0:01:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,But you told me that some years ago, \Nbefore you were in the truth, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.79,0:01:50.80,Default,,0,0,0,,you discovered that there were \Ntwo main interests you had in life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.80,0:01:52.88,Default,,0,0,0,,One of them had to do with a career choice. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.88,0:01:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you explain that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.01,0:01:56.18,Default,,0,0,0,,One was music.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.18,0:01:57.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Music. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.39,0:02:01.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, is this a picture of you?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.81,0:02:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,That was the old me.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.90,0:02:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Evidently, you were in a band.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.52,0:02:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we were at a competition at the time.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.03,0:02:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,That was one of your interests, \Nbut there was another. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.16,0:02:17.16,Default,,0,0,0,,What was that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.16,0:02:19.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Searching for the purpose of life.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.28,0:02:22.29,Default,,0,0,0,,And how did you \Ngo about searching for life’s purpose?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.29,0:02:24.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I read a lot of books\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:24.33,0:02:28.21,Default,,0,0,0,,—books about parapsychology, Buddhism, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.21,0:02:30.84,Default,,0,0,0,,spiritism, Tibetan Lamaism.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.84,0:02:33.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Amazing! \NThat’s a lot of books. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.01,0:02:38.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, at the time, though, \Nyou were dating your wife, Vicki. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.39,0:02:40.22,Default,,0,0,0,,What did she think of all these books? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.22,0:02:42.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Did she share your interest \Nin all this reading?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.85,0:02:44.35,Default,,0,0,0,,I wished she did. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.35,0:02:46.85,Default,,0,0,0,,But no, she did not. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.85,0:02:50.07,Default,,0,0,0,,To be honest, it’s not really easy \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:50.07,0:02:52.53,Default,,0,0,0,,to like to read those kinds of books\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.53,0:02:55.74,Default,,0,0,0,,—for example, The Book of the Dead.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:55.74,0:02:57.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The Book of the Dead? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.95,0:03:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I can see that’s not going \Nto be a very enjoyable book. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.70,0:03:04.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, was it only books? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.04,0:03:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Was that the only way \Nyou were searching for the purpose of life?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.71,0:03:12.50,Default,,0,0,0,,No, I was also experimenting \Nwith different states of mind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.50,0:03:15.38,Default,,0,0,0,,under the influence of drugs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.38,0:03:18.59,Default,,0,0,0,,During my hallucinations, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.59,0:03:21.85,Default,,0,0,0,,I had many things already “solved.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.85,0:03:23.56,Default,,0,0,0,,You had everything “solved.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.56,0:03:25.14,Default,,0,0,0,,This is what I thought. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.14,0:03:30.15,Default,,0,0,0,,But after I came to myself again, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.15,0:03:34.94,Default,,0,0,0,,I was again in the same room \Nand everything was the same. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.94,0:03:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So I was really, really disappointed. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.36,0:03:39.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And then I prayed to God. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.53,0:03:43.66,Default,,0,0,0,,I said: \N“God, I’m asking just for one thing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.66,0:03:48.29,Default,,0,0,0,,But whatever it is, just, please, \Nhelp me to be certain that I find the truth.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.29,0:03:50.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Very interesting. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.67,0:03:52.67,Default,,0,0,0,,So you prayed for Jehovah \Nto help you find the truth. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.67,0:03:55.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Of course, \Nyou didn’t know Jehovah at the time. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.67,0:03:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So how was your prayer answered?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.47,0:04:01.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Soon after that, I went to Germany. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.51,0:04:05.10,Default,,0,0,0,,I had the idea to form my music studio. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.10,0:04:07.10,Default,,0,0,0,,During my visit there, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.10,0:04:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,I understood that my uncle \Nand my aunt were Jehovah’s Witnesses.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.31,0:04:12.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And you never knew that before?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.73,0:04:14.69,Default,,0,0,0,,No. \NNo, I didn’t know.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.69,0:04:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what did they have in their home \Nthat would have been really exciting to you?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.53,0:04:25.37,Default,,0,0,0,,As all Jehovah’s Witnesses, \Nthey had a lot of theocratic books.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.37,0:04:27.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Ahh. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.08,0:04:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So, did you read the books?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.25,0:04:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, I read them a lot. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.04,0:04:33.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, I read a book daily.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.84,0:04:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.80,0:04:38.22,Default,,0,0,0,,So you get back home; \Nyou open up the suitcases. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.22,0:04:42.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And Vicki is there, \Nand she sees books. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.26,0:04:45.39,Default,,0,0,0,,And you were supposed \Nto bring home musical equipment. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.39,0:04:47.39,Default,,0,0,0,,What did she think about that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.39,0:04:52.94,Default,,0,0,0,,She thought, \N‘Now definitely he’s totally crazy.’\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.94,0:04:55.65,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what did you do?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.65,0:04:59.24,Default,,0,0,0,,I explained to her immediately \Nthat from now on \N
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.24,0:05:03.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I would like to live according to what I read \Nin these books and the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.91,0:05:08.37,Default,,0,0,0,,And I would also like it for her\N—that she also live like that. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.37,0:05:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,If this was OK with her, \Nwe could stay together. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.50,0:05:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If it was not OK with her, \Nwe were finished.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.55,0:05:18.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You like to be direct, don’t you?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.26,0:05:22.59,Default,,0,0,0,,I know, I was “very tactful.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.59,0:05:25.80,Default,,0,0,0,,But I also offered her \Nthe book Young People Ask.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.80,0:05:26.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Did she like that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.72,0:05:27.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.76,0:05:30.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, she liked it \Nmuch more than my ultimatum.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.64,0:05:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I see.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.52,0:05:34.52,Default,,0,0,0,,We started studying the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.52,0:05:38.15,Default,,0,0,0,,At the beginning, \Nmy wife started because of me, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.15,0:05:40.44,Default,,0,0,0,,but later \Nshe did this because of herself. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.44,0:05:45.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And after six months, \Nwe became unbaptized publishers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.28,0:05:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then we got married, \Nand we were baptized in 1994. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.25,0:05:53.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Immediately, we started full-time service, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.46,0:05:56.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and we served five years \Nas regular pioneers \N
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.59,0:06:00.59,Default,,0,0,0,,and then almost five years \Nas special pioneers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.59,0:06:05.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And now we’ve been \N13 years at the Serbia branch.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.51,0:06:07.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah has answered your prayer. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.14,0:06:08.43,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re satisfied; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.43,0:06:12.60,Default,,0,0,0,,you found the truth; \Nyou found the purpose in life. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.60,0:06:15.73,Default,,0,0,0,,But there’s still the music. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.73,0:06:19.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you have to give up \Nyour desire to play music, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.90,0:06:23.24,Default,,0,0,0,,to be involved in music, \Nespecially since you’ve come to Bethel now?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.24,0:06:25.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, in 2013, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.78,0:06:29.83,Default,,0,0,0,,there was an idea \Nthat we should start with a project \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.83,0:06:34.08,Default,,0,0,0,,of recording vocal renditions \Nof our theocratic songs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.08,0:06:39.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And my wife, Violeta, and I had the privilege \Nto participate in that project.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.25,0:06:42.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, was this just for the Serbia branch?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.63,0:06:46.26,Default,,0,0,0,,No, the plan was to record the songs \Nin four or five languages.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.26,0:06:48.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Four or five languages? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.47,0:06:50.47,Default,,0,0,0,,But would this mean, then, \Nthat you would travel \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.47,0:06:53.35,Default,,0,0,0,,around to different countries \Nsurrounding Serbia?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.35,0:06:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,No, the idea was that singers \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.27,0:06:59.52,Default,,0,0,0,,would come from other countries to Serbia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.52,0:07:02.19,Default,,0,0,0,,and they would be full-time singers \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.19,0:07:05.57,Default,,0,0,0,,for a period of time \Nuntil we finished that project.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.57,0:07:07.82,Default,,0,0,0,,That must have been \Na tremendous amount of work. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.82,0:07:09.95,Default,,0,0,0,,How did you get that accomplished?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.95,0:07:12.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it’s easier if we see a video, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.91,0:07:15.08,Default,,0,0,0,,and it will be much more understandable.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.08,0:07:19.42,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, good. \NLet’s watch the video.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.42,0:07:24.00,Default,,0,0,0,,One of the first things we needed \Nwas a recording studio. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.22,0:07:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So with the help of many, we built our own.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.18,0:07:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,A typical day began \Nwith a little music theory, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.23,0:07:43.03,Default,,0,0,0,,a little stretching,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.03,0:07:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and a brief review \Nof the song’s Scriptural theme.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.16,0:07:51.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Once they received a new song, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.53,0:07:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,they practiced in separate groups. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.58,0:07:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then they would all come together.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.04,0:08:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, it was time to record. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.05,0:08:09.05,Default,,0,0,0,,This resulted in 450 songs being recorded \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.05,0:08:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,in a period of 22 months.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.20,0:08:34.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Looking back, \Nthese songs were sung not just with words \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.70,0:08:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,but with hearts full of love for Jehovah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.04,0:08:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Look at them.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.80,0:08:51.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Those are nice greetings at the end there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.39,0:08:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, nice surprise.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.55,0:08:54.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I loved the way the chorus sounded. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.14,0:08:55.31,Default,,0,0,0,,You did a good job with them. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.31,0:08:58.93,Default,,0,0,0,,That must have been \Na tremendous amount of work, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.93,0:09:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,getting that all done, though, \Nin five different languages.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.06,0:09:05.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, the singers did a great job \Nand also all the crew. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.90,0:09:08.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And you really could see, \Nall the time, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.69,0:09:11.70,Default,,0,0,0,,their love for Jehovah \Nand love for the brotherhood. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.70,0:09:15.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And every day you could see \Na lot of their self-sacrificing spirit.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.99,0:09:18.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Saša, \Nlet me ask you one more question. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.37,0:09:20.91,Default,,0,0,0,,We saw the picture there \Nof you as a musician, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.91,0:09:23.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and I know you have \Nsome musical talent. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.58,0:09:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Possibly, you could have become famous. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:25.88,0:09:30.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you ever regret not pursuing \Nsome sort of a career in the world \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.30,0:09:34.26,Default,,0,0,0,,as opposed to giving your life \Nin full-time service to Jehovah?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.26,0:09:36.72,Default,,0,0,0,,As you said, I could be famous. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.72,0:09:41.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Or I could have become \Na drug addict and now be dead.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.02,0:09:43.48,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s a good point.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.48,0:09:46.61,Default,,0,0,0,,So no, no regrets at all. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:46.61,0:09:52.49,Default,,0,0,0,,I received much, \Nmuch more than I ever imagined. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.49,0:09:56.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And in my case, \Nfrom my first prayer till now, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.12,0:09:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah assured me \Nthat he’s really the “Hearer of prayer,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.91,0:10:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,as the psalmist \Nmentioned in Psalm 65:2.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.25,0:10:05.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Excellent! \NThank you so much, Saša, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.79,0:10:08.67,Default,,0,0,0,,for sharing \Nthese very heartfelt comments.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.67,0:10:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,You’re welcome.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.75,0:10:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:17.26,0:10:19.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you know what we’re going to do? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.31,0:10:21.39,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to give you the opportunity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.39,0:10:23.48,Default,,0,0,0,,to get to know some of the students \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.48,0:10:24.85,Default,,0,0,0,,in our audience. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.85,0:10:26.23,Default,,0,0,0,,We’re going to do an activity \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.23,0:10:28.69,Default,,0,0,0,,I call What’s My Favorite Scripture? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.69,0:10:31.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So we’re going to ask \Nthe students if they’ll volunteer \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.53,0:10:34.11,Default,,0,0,0,,and give us their favorite scripture and, \Nin a minute or less, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.11,0:10:37.70,Default,,0,0,0,,tell us what it says \Nand why it’s their favorite scripture.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.70,0:10:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.70,0:10:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,let’s see now. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.75,0:10:45.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Who would like to go first? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.37,0:10:49.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Shingirai Mapfumo from Zimbabwe.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.29,0:10:51.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Psalm 84:11.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.42,0:10:53.80,Default,,0,0,0,,And what does that say?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.80,0:10:57.30,Default,,0,0,0,,“For Jehovah God is a sun and a shield; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.30,0:10:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“he gives favor and glory. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:10:59.72,0:11:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“Jehovah will not hold back anything good \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.72,0:11:04.73,Default,,0,0,0,,from those walking in integrity.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.73,0:11:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, so tell us, \NWhy is that your favorite scripture?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.23,0:11:11.07,Default,,0,0,0,,During the economic crisis in Zimbabwe, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.07,0:11:13.86,Default,,0,0,0,,my pioneer partner and I ran out of food. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.86,0:11:16.28,Default,,0,0,0,,We were really starving, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.28,0:11:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,and physically we were so weak \Nthat we could not even function. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.74,0:11:21.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, we managed to go to town, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.70,0:11:24.45,Default,,0,0,0,,hoping that we could get \Nsome money from the bank. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.45,0:11:26.46,Default,,0,0,0,,There was a long queue, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.46,0:11:29.04,Default,,0,0,0,,and the bank \Nwas not giving any money either. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.04,0:11:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,We were so distraught. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.00,0:11:35.01,Default,,0,0,0,,At that moment \Nwhen we didn’t know what to do, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.01,0:11:40.14,Default,,0,0,0,,a truck from the branch office \Nbrought food supplies for us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.14,0:11:42.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Then it became so clear to me \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.64,0:11:44.64,Default,,0,0,0,,that Jehovah is “a shield,” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.64,0:11:48.56,Default,,0,0,0,,and he never “hold[s] back anything good” \Nfrom his loyal servants.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:48.56,0:11:51.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Amazing! Well, I can see why \Nthat’s your favorite scripture.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.11,0:11:53.11,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, who else? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.11,0:11:56.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s get Sister Tšèpang Mhlongo, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.65,0:11:58.49,Default,,0,0,0,,and she’s from South Africa.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.49,0:12:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,My favorite scripture is Psalm 68:5, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.37,0:12:04.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and it says about Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.58,0:12:08.71,Default,,0,0,0,,that he is the “father of the fatherless \Nand a protector of widows.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.71,0:12:10.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is that your favorite scripture?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.92,0:12:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I became motherless \Nwhen I was only one year old. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.50,0:12:19.34,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jehovah has provided me \Nwith hundreds of mothers around the globe, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.34,0:12:22.26,Default,,0,0,0,,both black and white. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.26,0:12:25.06,Default,,0,0,0,,And because our Bethel work \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.06,0:12:28.35,Default,,0,0,0,,involves traveling \Nall around the African continent \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.35,0:12:30.35,Default,,0,0,0,,working with the translators, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.35,0:12:32.86,Default,,0,0,0,,it makes it even more precious to me \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.86,0:12:36.03,Default,,0,0,0,,that I adopt this family wherever we go. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.03,0:12:39.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Truly, Jehovah has proved to be my Father \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.28,0:12:41.57,Default,,0,0,0,,and my Protector to this day.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.57,0:12:43.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Hmm, very touching. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.07,0:12:45.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And I’m sure that all \Nof those parents who have adopted you \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.74,0:12:48.00,Default,,0,0,0,,are proud to have you as a daughter.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.12,0:12:51.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Who else could tell us \Ntheir favorite scripture? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:51.83,0:12:56.09,Default,,0,0,0,,All right, \Nlet’s get Brother Sylvain Bois from Benin.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.09,0:12:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,It is Psalm 94:18, 19.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:12:59.09,0:13:01.09,Default,,0,0,0,,And what does it say?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.09,0:13:05.72,Default,,0,0,0,,“Your loyal love, O Jehovah, \Nkept supporting me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.72,0:13:08.39,Default,,0,0,0,,“When anxieties overwhelmed me, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:08.39,0:13:11.81,Default,,0,0,0,,you comforted and soothed me.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.81,0:13:15.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So tell us, \NWhy is that scripture special to you?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.94,0:13:19.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Years ago, when I was attending \NMinisterial Training School (MTS), \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.11,0:13:22.82,Default,,0,0,0,,I had a serious stroke \Nand I was hospitalized. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.82,0:13:25.58,Default,,0,0,0,,When I awoke from the coma, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.58,0:13:28.54,Default,,0,0,0,,I felt very happy because I was alive. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.54,0:13:30.62,Default,,0,0,0,,But also very discouraged \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.62,0:13:33.29,Default,,0,0,0,,because I thought \Neverything was over for me\N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.29,0:13:35.79,Default,,0,0,0,,—pioneer service, school, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.79,0:13:40.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and even my dream \Nto one day become a missionary. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.22,0:13:44.59,Default,,0,0,0,,But one of the instructors \Nand his wife came to the hospital, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.59,0:13:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,and they read me that verse. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.72,0:13:50.06,Default,,0,0,0,,And my heart was full of anxieties, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.06,0:13:52.39,Default,,0,0,0,,but I really felt that day that Jehovah \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.39,0:13:55.90,Default,,0,0,0,,was able to comfort me and soothe me. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.90,0:13:57.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And you know what? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.07,0:13:59.40,Default,,0,0,0,,One year later, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.40,0:14:01.86,Default,,0,0,0,,I was permitted to again attend MTS. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.86,0:14:03.86,Default,,0,0,0,,And a few months later, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.86,0:14:06.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah fulfilled another of my dreams, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.41,0:14:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,as I was assigned as a missionary in Africa.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.04,0:14:11.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Brother Bois, that was very touching. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.04,0:14:14.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you so much, and we’re so glad \Nto have you in this class of Gilead.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:14.37,0:14:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that’s all \Nthat we’re going to have time for.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.96,0:14:24.05,Default,,0,0,0,,So now it’s time to introduce our next guest, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.05,0:14:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and that would be Brother Paulo Maganha, \Nand he’s from Brazil.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.69,0:14:39.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Brother Maganha, \Nyou’re at the Brazil branch. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.98,0:14:43.24,Default,,0,0,0,,But you came into the truth \Nat nine years old, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.24,0:14:45.24,Default,,0,0,0,,at the same time as your mother. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.24,0:14:49.37,Default,,0,0,0,,And you went to the branch, \Nto Bethel, in your early 20’s, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.37,0:14:52.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and you’ve been there for 27 years. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.58,0:14:55.71,Default,,0,0,0,,What department \Ndo you work in at the branch now?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.71,0:14:58.21,Default,,0,0,0,,I am now in LDC for one and a half years.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.21,0:14:59.21,Default,,0,0,0,,LDC. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.21,0:15:03.63,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, would you just tell us, \NWhat does the LDC Department do?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.63,0:15:06.93,Default,,0,0,0,,LDC is \Nthe Local Design/Construction Department. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.93,0:15:09.01,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s responsible for the work of planning, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.01,0:15:13.18,Default,,0,0,0,,construction, and maintenance \Nof Kingdom Halls and Assembly Halls.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.18,0:15:17.10,Default,,0,0,0,,You have the LDC Department there at Bethel, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.10,0:15:19.48,Default,,0,0,0,,but who outside of Bethel \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.48,0:15:23.40,Default,,0,0,0,,works with building \NKingdom Halls and Assembly Halls?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.40,0:15:26.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Outside we have many brothers and sisters \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.24,0:15:29.66,Default,,0,0,0,,serving as construction servants, \Nconstruction volunteers, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.66,0:15:33.08,Default,,0,0,0,,remote volunteers, \Nand field representatives.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.08,0:15:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, this is—\NThis is the mystery.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:34.25,0:15:35.12,Default,,0,0,0,,This is our first mystery. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.12,0:15:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,What really, then, \Ndoes a field representative do?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.88,0:15:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, let’s just call them field rep. OK?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.00,0:15:43.80,Default,,0,0,0,,OK. \NField rep, I like that.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.80,0:15:48.05,Default,,0,0,0,,You could say that they are the eyes \Nand the ears of the LDC at the branch. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.05,0:15:51.18,Default,,0,0,0,,But what if I show you \Nsome pictures regarding the work?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.18,0:15:52.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I would love that!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.26,0:15:52.97,Default,,0,0,0,,OK. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.97,0:15:57.94,Default,,0,0,0,,At the first step, the office asks him \Nto investigate some congregation needs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.94,0:16:01.15,Default,,0,0,0,,He meets with the local elders \Nand the circuit overseer \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.15,0:16:03.15,Default,,0,0,0,,to determine the needs. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.15,0:16:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And later, he sends \Na recommendation to the office.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.57,0:16:08.86,Default,,0,0,0,,I see.\NSo if he has a large region,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.86,0:16:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,he may have to have \Nmany, many of these meetings \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.20,0:16:14.29,Default,,0,0,0,,and do a lot of research to determine \Nwhat the needs are for Kingdom Halls.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.29,0:16:15.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.54,0:16:17.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Once the project is approved, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.29,0:16:21.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the next step is to search \Nfor appropriate land, a property. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.29,0:16:23.75,Default,,0,0,0,,To do that, \Nhe goes to the Internet, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.75,0:16:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,consults real estate agents, \Nlocal brothers, neighbors. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.26,0:16:31.26,Default,,0,0,0,,To find the right property \Nat the right cost can be very time consuming \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.26,0:16:34.60,Default,,0,0,0,,and requires of him \Na lot of skills and abilities. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.60,0:16:38.89,Default,,0,0,0,,And the field rep \Nis also responsible for getting the permits, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.89,0:16:40.90,Default,,0,0,0,,the approvals, for construction. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.90,0:16:44.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And he visits \Nseveral different agencies every day \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.52,0:16:48.19,Default,,0,0,0,,to get the permits to have \Neverything approved by the government.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.19,0:16:51.45,Default,,0,0,0,,In big cities, he may have to stand \Nin line after line after line. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.45,0:16:52.53,Default,,0,0,0,,This could take—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.53,0:16:55.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah. And in bigger cities, \Nit can take even some weeks \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.58,0:16:57.91,Default,,0,0,0,,or months \Nto get everything approved. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.91,0:17:02.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Finally, when everything is approved, \Nthe construction group starts the work. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.13,0:17:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,And you can see him again visiting the site \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.63,0:17:08.46,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to give some technical support \Nto the construction overseer.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.46,0:17:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So, now, does he stay on the site \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.68,0:17:12.34,Default,,0,0,0,,when a building is being built?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.34,0:17:14.60,Default,,0,0,0,,No, he returns to his office \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.60,0:17:18.85,Default,,0,0,0,,but remains in contact with the group \Nto give some remote support. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.85,0:17:22.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Especially when some big issues \Narise at the site, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.77,0:17:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,the construction overseer \Ncan always count on his good support.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.32,0:17:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, good. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.32,0:17:30.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I notice in this picture, \Nbehind the field representative, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.19,0:17:32.07,Default,,0,0,0,,we see a sister pictured there. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.07,0:17:33.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Who might that be?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.70,0:17:35.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, if he’s married, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.70,0:17:39.16,Default,,0,0,0,,his wife can do \Nlots of work to help him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.16,0:17:43.50,Default,,0,0,0,,But if he is not, he can count \Non a local volunteer to help him. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.50,0:17:46.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Once the project is concluded, \Nhe visits the site again, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.38,0:17:48.38,Default,,0,0,0,,now to do the commissioning \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.38,0:17:51.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and to make sure that everything \Nwas done according to the plans.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.63,0:17:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,So, evidently, his job is done now.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.01,0:17:55.47,Default,,0,0,0,,No, not yet. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.47,0:17:59.02,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s also responsible \Nfor giving training to local brothers \N
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.02,0:18:01.06,Default,,0,0,0,,to properly maintain the building.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.06,0:18:03.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow! \NSo you have helped solve this mystery. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.98,0:18:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,He does have a lot of work to do. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:07.32,0:18:11.69,Default,,0,0,0,,But really, does working \Non one project keep him busy?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.69,0:18:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,No, it is not just one, Brother Stovall. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.36,0:18:16.20,Default,,0,0,0,,They are very busy and productive workers. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.20,0:18:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,On average, each field rep \Ncan be working on 10 to 15 projects \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.75,0:18:23.12,Default,,0,0,0,,in different phases but at the same time.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.12,0:18:24.96,Default,,0,0,0,,My goodness!\NThat’s amazing!\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.96,0:18:28.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So they really do \Nan amazing amount of work then. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.42,0:18:30.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Paulo, I understand that at your branch, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.88,0:18:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,you’ve come up with a very innovative idea \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.88,0:18:37.72,Default,,0,0,0,,regarding Assembly Halls and Kingdom Halls. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.72,0:18:39.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you explain that to us?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.26,0:18:43.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we have done what is called \Nan expandable Kingdom Hall.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.43,0:18:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Expandable Kingdom Hall? \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.56,0:18:49.69,Default,,0,0,0,,Saša, do you have \Nexpandable Kingdom Halls in Serbia?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.69,0:18:51.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Not that I’m aware of.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.07,0:18:53.28,Default,,0,0,0,,I can’t even imagine. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.28,0:18:55.45,Default,,0,0,0,,How do you expand a Kingdom Hall?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.45,0:18:58.62,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, what if we see a brief video about this?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.62,0:19:01.00,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, I’d like that.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.79,0:19:06.79,Default,,0,0,0,,At first, \Nit looks like a normal Kingdom Hall. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.79,0:19:11.92,Default,,0,0,0,,But something wonderful happens \Nwhen the back walls are lifted.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.92,0:19:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s now large enough to hold \Nan entire assembly or convention.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.01,0:19:23.77,Default,,0,0,0,,But before we can meet there, \Nit has to be cleaned. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.77,0:19:27.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Chairs are rented and arranged. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:27.27,0:19:30.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And audio and video equipment must be set up \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:30.69,0:19:33.07,Default,,0,0,0,,so that no matter where you sit, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.07,0:19:36.86,Default,,0,0,0,,you won’t miss anything.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.86,0:19:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,All the hard work is worth it \Nwhen you see how much the friends benefit.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.22,0:20:02.06,Default,,0,0,0,,When the special weekend of activity is over \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.06,0:20:04.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and the walls are lowered, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.22,0:20:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,it goes right back \Nto being a Kingdom Hall again.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.79,0:20:28.16,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s our family there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:28.16,0:20:30.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh-huh. \NThey sent you some spirited greetings.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.58,0:20:31.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.33,0:20:33.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And what a brilliant way \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.34,0:20:36.21,Default,,0,0,0,,to get the most out of a building \Nand save money! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.21,0:20:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Brother Maganha, \NI just want to ask you, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.55,0:20:42.89,Default,,0,0,0,,What has impressed you the most \Nabout working with the LDC Department?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:42.89,0:20:47.06,Default,,0,0,0,,What really touched my heart \Nis to see the spirit of willingness to help \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.06,0:20:50.14,Default,,0,0,0,,shown by all those involved with the LDC. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.14,0:20:53.11,Default,,0,0,0,,You know, these brothers \Nand sisters have left their families, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.11,0:20:55.11,Default,,0,0,0,,their houses, their friends behind \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.11,0:20:56.98,Default,,0,0,0,,to work with these projects. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.98,0:21:00.15,Default,,0,0,0,,All these sacrifices are done out of love\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.15,0:21:03.37,Default,,0,0,0,,—love for our brotherhood \Nand especially love for Jehovah. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.37,0:21:07.66,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s the reason \Nthat I really, really appreciate their work.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.66,0:21:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you, Brother Maganha. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:09.04,0:21:12.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Obviously, those brothers \Nand sisters that work with LDC \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.17,0:21:14.38,Default,,0,0,0,,set a good example for the rest of us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.38,0:21:15.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you very much.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.59,0:21:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,My pleasure.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.68,0:21:23.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Brother Komaromi, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.18,0:21:26.26,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s time for you to give us \Na sample of your musical talent. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.26,0:21:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Would you go and join our band?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.48,0:21:37.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Recently, the Governing Body \Nhas given us loving encouragement \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.32,0:21:41.45,Default,,0,0,0,,through our regional convention program \Nto never give up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.45,0:21:44.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the Gilead students have written a song \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.45,0:21:48.58,Default,,0,0,0,,that goes right along with that spirit \Nand that theme. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.58,0:21:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s entitled “We’ll Never Let Go.”\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.38,0:24:46.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought that was a thrilling song.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.26,0:24:49.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You brothers and sisters\Ndid a marvelous job on that.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.26,0:24:51.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And you know what I liked about the song too\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.26,0:24:53.72,Default,,0,0,0,,is that it gets progressively more modern\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.72,0:24:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,as you go through the song.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.31,0:24:58.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So it really says to me that our organization \N
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.81,0:25:00.81,Default,,0,0,0,,in its modern-day history, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.81,0:25:03.31,Default,,0,0,0,,even in early times, has never given up,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:03.31,0:25:05.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and we will never give up. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.69,0:25:07.69,Default,,0,0,0,,And it’s so joyful. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.69,0:25:10.24,Default,,0,0,0,,It says that we’re going to endure with joy. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.24,0:25:11.74,Default,,0,0,0,,No one can take that away from us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.74,0:25:15.45,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s Jehovah’s gift through his holy spirit.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.45,0:25:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Now it’s time to introduce our final guest, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.45,0:25:23.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and that is Sister Angela Khang \Nfrom the United States.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.34,0:25:36.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Angela, you are one \Nof the single sisters in our class,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:36.14,0:25:39.31,Default,,0,0,0,,but where in the United States \Ndo you serve?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.31,0:25:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m at the remote translation office (RTO) \Nin Sacramento, California, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.14,0:25:44.98,Default,,0,0,0,,and they translate\Ninto the Hmong language there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.98,0:25:47.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I have to confess\N—the Hmong language—\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.98,0:25:50.61,Default,,0,0,0,,I never knew until very recently \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.61,0:25:53.78,Default,,0,0,0,,that there was such a language \Nas the Hmong language. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.78,0:25:56.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And I didn’t realize \Nthere was a Hmong people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.99,0:25:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Why is that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.37,0:26:02.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, for a long time, the Hmong story \Nwas kept a secret from the American public.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.12,0:26:04.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Now this is another one of our mysteries \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.96,0:26:07.71,Default,,0,0,0,,because why would it be \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.71,0:26:13.26,Default,,0,0,0,,that someone would try to keep \Nthe existence of a whole culture secret?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.26,0:26:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, during the Vietnam War, \Nwhich was a very unpopular conflict, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.64,0:26:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,many U.S. citizens \Ndidn’t want the war to expand. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.22,0:26:22.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So the U.S. government \Nactually went to Southeast Asia, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.81,0:26:24.81,Default,,0,0,0,,and they secretly recruited the Hmong men \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.81,0:26:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,who were living in the hill tribes of Laos \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:26.86,0:26:29.32,Default,,0,0,0,,to fight Communism in that part of the world. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.32,0:26:32.28,Default,,0,0,0,,In the end, about 40,000 Hmong men \Nwere killed in that war, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.28,0:26:34.70,Default,,0,0,0,,and so that’s about 1 in 4 Hmong men. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.70,0:26:36.70,Default,,0,0,0,,So every family lost someone.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.70,0:26:38.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Forty thousand men. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:38.70,0:26:42.16,Default,,0,0,0,,I don’t think that people \Nreally are aware of that fact, are they?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.16,0:26:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,No. Many historians \Ncall that conflict the Secret War.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:46.00,0:26:49.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Looking at our monitor here, \Nwhat is it we are seeing here?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.46,0:26:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,This was an exhibit \Nshowcasing the Hmong experience\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.71,0:26:53.72,Default,,0,0,0,,—how they came to the U.S. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.72,0:26:56.80,Default,,0,0,0,,And it’s a wall of unknown soldiers \Nwho fought in the war, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.80,0:26:59.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and they were asking the Hmong community\Nto identify their loved ones.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.76,0:27:02.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So a few in our congregation \Nknew some of those men.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.60,0:27:04.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.02,0:27:06.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, \Nas I think back to the history of that war, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.48,0:27:09.86,Default,,0,0,0,,at some point in time, \Nthe United States pulled out of Vietnam. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.86,0:27:11.86,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what happened then \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.86,0:27:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,to the Hmong that were left there \Nin Vietnam when the U.S. pulled out?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.16,0:27:20.66,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a desperate situation \Nbecause there was an aggressive campaign \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.66,0:27:23.04,Default,,0,0,0,,to capture and kill \Nany of the remaining Hmong families, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.04,0:27:26.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and so many of them \Nhad to find a way to escape. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:26.46,0:27:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And so we see that here in this photo. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.46,0:27:32.46,Default,,0,0,0,,This is Long Tieng Air Base in 1975. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.46,0:27:34.84,Default,,0,0,0,,About 30,000 Hmong people \Nconverged on that airport, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.84,0:27:36.84,Default,,0,0,0,,hoping to find a way out. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.84,0:27:40.10,Default,,0,0,0,,But only about 2,500 were airlifted\N—the more prominent officials.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:40.10,0:27:41.18,Default,,0,0,0,,I see.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.18,0:27:42.81,Default,,0,0,0,,You can see \Nthat those thousands of people there \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.81,0:27:44.81,Default,,0,0,0,,are not going \Nto fit on that airplane. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:44.81,0:27:47.56,Default,,0,0,0,,So all those thousands that were left behind,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:47.56,0:27:49.56,Default,,0,0,0,,what happened to them?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.56,0:27:51.57,Default,,0,0,0,,They were pretty much left on their own, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.57,0:27:55.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and they had to find their way out \Nalong with thousands of other families. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.03,0:27:56.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And so that’s what happened to my family. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.78,0:27:59.66,Default,,0,0,0,,They found their way \Nacross the Mekong River into Thailand, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.66,0:28:01.66,Default,,0,0,0,,and they were placed in refugee camps.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.66,0:28:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.37,0:28:04.66,Default,,0,0,0,,So who are we seeing \Na picture of here now on the monitor?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.66,0:28:08.21,Default,,0,0,0,,This is my father \Nin a Thailand refugee camp \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:08.21,0:28:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and my mother,\Nmy grandmother, and my uncle.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.46,0:28:16.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So your family managed to survive \Nby fleeing into Thailand \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.92,0:28:18.93,Default,,0,0,0,,and getting into the refugee camp. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.93,0:28:22.30,Default,,0,0,0,,But then how did they get \Nto the United States?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.30,0:28:25.31,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1979, \Nthey were sponsored to the United States. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.31,0:28:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,And the Hmong culture is patriarchal, \Nso you stick close with your clan. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:29.35,0:28:34.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And so my entire clan ended up in California, \Nand they settled in South Sacramento.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.23,0:28:39.11,Default,,0,0,0,,I can imagine that this experience \Nmust have been a tremendous amount of loss \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.11,0:28:42.24,Default,,0,0,0,,for the Hmong people, Hmong families.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.24,0:28:44.45,Default,,0,0,0,,My father lost his mother \Nwhen they were fleeing; \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.45,0:28:45.87,Default,,0,0,0,,he lost his brother. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.87,0:28:47.87,Default,,0,0,0,,He saw many people lose their lives. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.87,0:28:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Many clans were separated. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.42,0:28:51.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Some of their relatives ended up in France, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.42,0:28:53.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and the rest of them \Nended up in the United States. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.88,0:28:57.51,Default,,0,0,0,,And then when they settled here, \Nmy mom lost her hearing. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.51,0:28:59.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So it was just an added stress \Nin their lives.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:28:59.55,0:29:03.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So how did all this suffering and loss, \Nhow did it affect your mother?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:03.68,0:29:05.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Even though her background is animist, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.68,0:29:09.06,Default,,0,0,0,,she knew that the Bible was a holy book \Nthat would teach her about the Creator. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.06,0:29:11.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So she found comfort in reading the Bible. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.52,0:29:15.02,Default,,0,0,0,,And she started to collect \Ndifferent Bibles from different translations \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.02,0:29:17.82,Default,,0,0,0,,and comparing them to try \Nto understand what she was reading. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.82,0:29:20.70,Default,,0,0,0,,And every night she would pray \Nwith me and my sister. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.70,0:29:23.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And so from a young age, \Nwe were taught that God is real, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:23.66,0:29:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,even though we didn’t know Jehovah yet.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.24,0:29:28.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Wow, very, very interesting. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.70,0:29:31.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So she was \Nreally, really looking for the truth. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:31.79,0:29:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,So how did she eventually find the truth?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.88,0:29:38.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, in the meantime, \Nmy uncle (the one who was pictured earlier) \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:38.05,0:29:41.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and his wife started studying the Bible, \Nand they came into the truth. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.01,0:29:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And they asked a sister \Nto come and study with my mom, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.76,0:29:46.14,Default,,0,0,0,,and soon my entire family was studying. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:46.14,0:29:48.18,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1996, my mom was baptized. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:48.18,0:29:51.31,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1997, my sister and I were baptized.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:51.31,0:29:55.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Amazing! So, now, \Nyou were baptized at the age of 12, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.36,0:29:58.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and then you \Nstarted pioneering at the age of 15.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.61,0:29:59.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:29:59.61,0:30:01.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, first of all, \Nyou were in an English congregation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.78,0:30:04.07,Default,,0,0,0,,But what changed that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:04.07,0:30:07.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Our circuit overseer came through, \Nand he was telling us about a Hmong group \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.95,0:30:10.08,Default,,0,0,0,,that had formed in our sister congregation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:10.08,0:30:12.50,Default,,0,0,0,,And he told us we had \Nno reason to be in English, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.50,0:30:14.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and he was right. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.88,0:30:17.13,Default,,0,0,0,,So as a family, \Nwe moved over to the Hmong group, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:17.13,0:30:20.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and in 1999, that group \Nbecame the very first Hmong congregation. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.88,0:30:22.63,Default,,0,0,0,,So that made us very happy.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.63,0:30:25.97,Default,,0,0,0,,So you were associated \Nwith the very first Hmong congregation \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.97,0:30:26.97,Default,,0,0,0,,anywhere in the world.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.97,0:30:27.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.64,0:30:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Amazing! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.52,0:30:32.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, later you toured Bethel, \Nand that had a profound effect on you. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.81,0:30:34.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Can you tell us about that?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:34.19,0:30:37.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we came to Bethel,\Nand a brother in Translation Services\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.90,0:30:40.90,Default,,0,0,0,,found out we were coming through,\Nso he wanted to meet with us.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.90,0:30:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And he sat us girls down,\Nand he told us,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.28,0:30:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,“You have something you can give to Jehovah, \Nand that’s your language.” \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.03,0:30:49.03,Default,,0,0,0,,So it really got me thinking \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.03,0:30:52.25,Default,,0,0,0,,about what I could do \Nto really support the field. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:52.25,0:30:55.12,Default,,0,0,0,,So I went home,\Nand I really worked on my language \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.12,0:30:56.67,Default,,0,0,0,,and worked on supporting the group. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.67,0:30:59.25,Default,,0,0,0,,And in 2007 \N
Dialogue: 0,0:30:59.25,0:31:01.26,Default,,0,0,0,,when Bethel came looking for translators, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.26,0:31:04.09,Default,,0,0,0,,this same brother came out \Nand he interviewed a group of us. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.09,0:31:07.18,Default,,0,0,0,,And shortly after that,\Nmy mom and another brother and I\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.18,0:31:10.93,Default,,0,0,0,,were invited to serve \Non the Hmong translation team \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.93,0:31:13.10,Default,,0,0,0,,at the first RTO \Nhere in the U.S. branch.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.10,0:31:14.14,Default,,0,0,0,,My goodness! \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.14,0:31:17.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So the first Hmong congregation \Nanywhere in the world \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:17.94,0:31:21.32,Default,,0,0,0,,and the first RTO for the U.S. branch. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.32,0:31:25.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Jehovah certainly has blessed you \Nwith some wonderful privileges. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.32,0:31:26.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Could you just tell us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.78,0:31:30.49,Default,,0,0,0,,What’s it like working \Nat the RTO from day to day?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.49,0:31:31.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Sure. \NWould you like to see a video?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:31.91,0:31:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, we would.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.37,0:31:41.13,Default,,0,0,0,,At the Hmong RTO, \Nmany hands help in the translation work.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:41.13,0:31:44.92,Default,,0,0,0,,When questions come up, \Nwe’re not left on our own. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:44.92,0:31:49.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The Translation Services Department \Nis always ready to provide support.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.26,0:31:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Once everything is approved, \Nit’s time to record. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.14,0:31:59.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Since Hmong wasn’t a written language \Nuntil the 1950’s, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.48,0:32:03.65,Default,,0,0,0,,audio publications are very important \Nto the Hmong field.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.65,0:32:07.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Some support the RTO \Nin other valuable ways too, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:07.07,0:32:10.20,Default,,0,0,0,,such as cooking and cleaning.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.20,0:32:14.12,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the best feeling \Nto talk to the Hmong people \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:14.12,0:32:16.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and to show them \Nsomething in their language. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:16.46,0:32:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,You can see how it touches their heart.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:21.71,0:32:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, we have many interested ones \Nattend our meetings.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.76,0:32:31.05,Default,,0,0,0,,As the Hmong field continues to grow, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:31.05,0:32:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,many are learning our language \Nto help support the preaching work.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:37.64,0:32:40.98,Default,,0,0,0,,When we get together,\Nwe have a great time\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:40.98,0:32:42.94,Default,,0,0,0,,—with good food, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:42.94,0:32:46.78,Default,,0,0,0,,association,\Nwatching the kids play.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:46.78,0:32:50.03,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s obvious to everyone in the community \N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.03,0:32:52.20,Default,,0,0,0,,that we’re not just a congregation\N
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.20,0:32:55.00,Default,,0,0,0,,—we’re a family.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:05.63,0:33:08.88,Default,,0,0,0,,That is a wonderful video, really. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.88,0:33:10.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Angela, could you just tell us, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.88,0:33:13.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Why does the work done at the RTO \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.39,0:33:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,fill such a great need \Namong the Hmong people?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:16.93,0:33:20.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, the Hmong are a people\Nwithout a country, and throughout history,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:20.02,0:33:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,they’ve been pushed\Nfrom one location to another.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.31,0:33:25.15,Default,,0,0,0,,They were pushed out of China\Nin the late 1800’s, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.15,0:33:26.57,Default,,0,0,0,,they were pushed out of Laos,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:26.57,0:33:29.49,Default,,0,0,0,,and from there \Nthey were scattered across the world\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:29.49,0:33:30.86,Default,,0,0,0,,—to the U.S., \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.86,0:33:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,to France, to Australia. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.87,0:33:34.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And so for many of the Hmong brothers, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:34.87,0:33:37.83,Default,,0,0,0,,they feel like a forgotten people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:37.83,0:33:41.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Excuse me, \NI watched this video for the first time here.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.75,0:33:44.75,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the first time she’s seen the video.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.75,0:33:46.17,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s the first time.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.17,0:33:48.17,Default,,0,0,0,,So it’s, it’s moving.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:48.17,0:33:51.80,Default,,0,0,0,,So many of the Hmong brothers \Nfeel like a forgotten people. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.80,0:33:56.39,Default,,0,0,0,,But the work at the RTO is a reminder\Nthat Jehovah hasn’t forgotten them.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:56.39,0:33:58.39,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, he invites them\N
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.39,0:34:01.89,Default,,0,0,0,,to become part of an international clan\N—a brotherhood.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.89,0:34:04.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And when they respond to that invitation,\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:04.10,0:34:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,they find something\Nthat they’ve been looking for all along.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.02,0:34:09.03,Default,,0,0,0,,They finally find a place\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:09.03,0:34:11.32,Default,,0,0,0,,—a permanent home—\Nunder God’s Kingdom.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.32,0:34:13.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you for those heartfelt comments. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:13.32,0:34:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Really, those were very nice.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:16.16,0:34:18.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, Sister Khang,\Nwe have a little surprise for you.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:18.95,0:34:23.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We really want the audience to know that, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:23.29,0:34:25.29,Default,,0,0,0,,well, the work done at the Hmong RTO \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:25.29,0:34:27.63,Default,,0,0,0,,is not just for the United States, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.63,0:34:30.92,Default,,0,0,0,,but the effect\Nreaches clear around the world\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.92,0:34:31.97,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.97,0:34:35.26,Default,,0,0,0,,we have caught up \Nwith a congregation in northern Thailand. \N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:35.26,0:34:39.01,Default,,0,0,0,,And I know this is a surprise;\Nwe did not rehearse this.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:39.01,0:34:41.27,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we did not.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.27,0:34:43.27,Default,,0,0,0,,But we’re going to show you, if you’d like.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.27,0:34:44.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:34:44.14,0:34:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Watch this.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:18.05,0:35:20.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, obviously,\Nthey are grateful for the work\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.10,0:35:23.43,Default,,0,0,0,,you brothers and sisters do in that RTO.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:23.43,0:35:26.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Wasn’t this a thrilling occasion?\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.27,0:35:31.23,Default,,0,0,0,,It was wonderful, enjoyable,\Nto get to know these brothers and sisters.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:31.23,0:35:36.24,Default,,0,0,0,,We wish that Jehovah continues\Nto bless you in your faithful service to him\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:36.24,0:35:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,until the next time we get together \Non The Inside Story.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.34,0:35:55.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you very much, Brother Stovall,\Nfor sharing with us The Inside Story.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.05,0:35:59.05,Default,,0,0,0,,We appreciate very much\Nyour letting us in on it.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.05,0:36:02.18,Default,,0,0,0,,But I have to admit\Nthat this is the first Gilead graduation\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.18,0:36:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,I’ve ever been to where\NI couldn’t help but pat my foot back there.\N
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.73,0:36:10.46,Default,,0,0,0,,I’m just so glad I was behind the curtain.\N
